35
00:18:48,741 --> 00:18:51,063
[SPEAKER_25]: 26038, offered by Vice President Lazzaro and Councilor Tseng.

36
00:18:51,623 --> 00:18:54,085
[SPEAKER_25]: Resolution to recognize and celebrate Black History Month.

37
00:18:54,746 --> 00:19:00,330
[SPEAKER_25]: Whereas February is recognized nationwide as Black History Month, a time to honor the history, resilience, and achievements of black Americans.

38
00:19:00,590 --> 00:19:09,397
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas black Americans have shaped our nation and our commonwealth through leadership and civic life, education, labor, arts, business, science, and the ongoing pursuit of justice and equality.

39
00:19:10,017 --> 00:19:19,544
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas Medford's own history includes the longstanding black community of West Medford, whose residents have built institutions, sustained cultural traditions, and strengthened the civic life of our city across generations.

40
00:19:19,884 --> 00:19:29,791
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas Medford's early history includes the enslavement of black individuals, including those connected to the Brooks Estate, and acknowledging this history is essential to telling a full and honest story of our city.

41
00:19:30,432 --> 00:19:34,675
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas today black Americans, including immigrants and families across the African diaspora,

42
00:19:34,915 --> 00:19:39,836
[SPEAKER_25]: continue to shape Medford's neighborhoods, schools, houses of worship, small businesses, arts, and public life.

43
00:19:40,576 --> 00:19:48,958
[SPEAKER_25]: Whereas Black History is American history and its recognition strengthens our shared understanding of our past and our collective responsibility for a more just and inclusive future.

44
00:19:49,459 --> 00:20:03,162
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford City Council recognizes Black History Month and celebrates the contributions of black residents past and present to the life of our city, and be it further resolved that the city recommits itself to advancing equity, opportunity, and belonging for all members of our community.

45
00:20:04,217 --> 00:20:05,157
[SPEAKER_25]: Vice President Lazzaro.

46
00:20:06,258 --> 00:20:06,698
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

47
00:20:07,958 --> 00:20:09,619
[SPEAKER_18]: Very pleased to offer this.

48
00:20:10,979 --> 00:20:23,384
[SPEAKER_18]: I was also honored to be the Medford City Council representative at the Black History Month celebration that was held right here in the chambers last weekend.

49
00:20:24,204 --> 00:20:25,905
[SPEAKER_18]: And it was on President's Day.

50
00:20:26,726 --> 00:20:49,087
[SPEAKER_18]: And when that event was hosted by our Office of Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion, run by Frances Nwaje, which was a really beautiful event, a great community event, even brought people in from other communities, and it's a great opportunity for people to come together and really appreciate and enjoy

51
00:20:50,127 --> 00:21:00,331
[SPEAKER_18]: what Medford has to offer, food, celebration, our college students, our high school students, and just a great celebration of our community.

52
00:21:01,231 --> 00:21:12,895
[SPEAKER_18]: And something that I mentioned during that event was that Medford has, in addition to a wealth of culture today, also has a deep well of history.

53
00:21:13,615 --> 00:21:16,856
[SPEAKER_18]: And a lot of that history is a little bit uncomfortable when it relates to

54
00:21:18,497 --> 00:21:28,248
[SPEAKER_18]: black Americans and our involvement, unfortunately, in the triangle trade and in slavery, and that legacy of slavery carries forward today.

55
00:21:29,249 --> 00:21:34,055
[SPEAKER_18]: One of our historic buildings is the Royal House and Slave Quarters, which is now a museum.

56
00:21:34,982 --> 00:22:00,351
[SPEAKER_18]: and the royal family was one of the first funders of Harvard University, really gave seed money to Harvard and allowed them to begin, and they were slaveholders, and that building, one of the buildings on that campus is, the campus of the Royal House and Slave Quarters is one of the only remaining freestanding slave quarters that is still in the Northeast, and it is a great,

57
00:22:02,072 --> 00:22:07,037
[SPEAKER_18]: museum now, great way to still see what that would have looked like in the 17th century.

58
00:22:07,377 --> 00:22:23,313
[SPEAKER_18]: And, you know, it's important for us to still revisit that history and understand how those people's lives were and how that legacy is carried forward now and what we can do to understand that history and how it affects us today.

59
00:22:24,334 --> 00:22:26,375
[SPEAKER_18]: And we also have the slave wall.

60
00:22:26,415 --> 00:22:31,277
[SPEAKER_18]: We also have the memorial at the Salem Street Burial Ground in Medford.

61
00:22:31,337 --> 00:22:35,640
[SPEAKER_18]: These are things that are representative of our past.

62
00:22:37,220 --> 00:22:50,987
[SPEAKER_18]: And they're not necessarily joyful, but there are ways to find joy and celebration when we understand what people in our community are able to make of

63
00:22:52,148 --> 00:23:04,770
[SPEAKER_18]: an experience that was tragic in the past and is now something that has built resilience and self-belief and

64
00:23:07,655 --> 00:23:20,882
[SPEAKER_18]: So, again, I was very honored to do this, and I'm very honored to be part of Medford's present and part of a community that is very strong and very present in this moment now.

65
00:23:21,562 --> 00:23:29,146
[SPEAKER_18]: And just the last thing I'll say, because I've talked for too long, is that West Medford is one of the oldest continuous black communities

66
00:23:29,766 --> 00:23:33,309
[SPEAKER_18]: in America and the West Medford Community Center is where my kids go to after school.

67
00:23:34,109 --> 00:23:53,764
[SPEAKER_18]: And that community center has been in operation for a very long time and they just recently had a great success last year and lobbied State Department, the Department of Conservation and Recreation to build a path from the back of their center to the Duggar Park area and the river over there.

68
00:23:54,004 --> 00:23:58,067
[SPEAKER_18]: And it was completed recently and it's a beautiful path and it's a great,

69
00:23:59,048 --> 00:24:08,375
[SPEAKER_18]: safer way for kids and seniors to get across to basketball courts, and the river, and the walking paths over there, and the pickleball courts, and the tennis courts, and the playground.

70
00:24:09,255 --> 00:24:13,898
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's because of the resilience and the grit of today's black Americans in Medford.

71
00:24:14,259 --> 00:24:19,242
[SPEAKER_18]: And I'm so grateful to be able to celebrate Black History Month here in Medford every year.

72
00:24:20,043 --> 00:24:20,343
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

73
00:24:21,243 --> 00:24:22,204
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you, Vice President Lazzaro.

74
00:24:22,264 --> 00:24:22,965
[SPEAKER_23]: Councilor Tsengh.

75
00:24:23,825 --> 00:24:26,408
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you, Council President Bears.

76
00:24:27,669 --> 00:24:32,113
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you, Vice President Lazzaro, for co-sponsoring this with me as well.

77
00:24:33,214 --> 00:24:41,962
[SPEAKER_23]: February is a time to honor the history, the resilience, and the achievement of black Americans, not as a separate chapter of our history, but as an essential part of it.

78
00:24:43,003 --> 00:24:47,428
[SPEAKER_23]: Black history is American history, it's Massachusetts history, and it's Medford history as well.

79
00:24:48,497 --> 00:25:02,684
[SPEAKER_23]: Black Americans have shaped our nation and our commonwealth and our city through leadership in civic life, in education, in labor and work, in arts, business, science, and the ongoing pursuit of justice and equality here.

80
00:25:03,945 --> 00:25:13,970
[SPEAKER_23]: Here in Medford, we're home to the longstanding black community of West Medford where generations of residents have built institutions and strengthened the civic life of our city.

81
00:25:15,929 --> 00:25:22,093
[SPEAKER_23]: Shiloh Baptist Church has long been a cornerstone of that work, and I want to be sure that they get the recognition as well.

82
00:25:22,833 --> 00:25:36,282
[SPEAKER_23]: They helped to establish the Mystic Valley NAACP and the West Medford Community Center, organizations that contribute so much to Medford and have been pivotal in preserving and uplifting black history locally.

83
00:25:37,167 --> 00:25:40,409
[SPEAKER_23]: At the same time, Medford's black community continues to grow and evolve.

84
00:25:41,090 --> 00:25:50,817
[SPEAKER_23]: Black immigrants from across Africa and the Caribbean bring extraordinary energy, entrepreneurship, faith traditions, and cultural richness to our neighborhoods.

85
00:25:51,477 --> 00:26:02,745
[SPEAKER_23]: They're small business experts and owners, educators, healthcare workers, artists, and public servants whose leadership strengthens our schools, our economy, and our shared sense of belonging.

86
00:26:03,764 --> 00:26:09,509
[SPEAKER_23]: As Vice President Lazzaro said, recognizing Black History Month also means telling a full and honest story.

87
00:26:10,430 --> 00:26:17,776
[SPEAKER_23]: Medford's early history includes the enslavement of black individuals, including those connected to the Brooks Estate and the Royal House.

88
00:26:19,097 --> 00:26:27,405
[SPEAKER_23]: Acknowledging that history is not about blame, it's about truth, resilience, and about ensuring we build a more just and even joyful future together.

89
00:26:28,815 --> 00:26:39,446
[SPEAKER_23]: This resolution both celebrates the contributions of black residents, past and present, and recommits us to advancing equity, opportunity, and belonging for everyone in our community.

90
00:26:40,026 --> 00:26:50,156
[SPEAKER_23]: That work belongs to all of us, and I'm proud tonight that tonight we stand together to recognize Black History Month and to reaffirm our commitment to a more inclusive Medford.

91
00:26:50,496 --> 00:26:50,777
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you.

92
00:26:52,741 --> 00:26:53,822
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, Councilor Tseng.

93
00:26:54,502 --> 00:26:57,924
[SPEAKER_25]: On the motion of Vice President Lazzaro, seconded by Councilor Tseng to approve.

94
00:26:58,344 --> 00:26:59,185
[SPEAKER_25]: All those in favor?

95
00:27:00,165 --> 00:27:00,565
[SPEAKER_25]: Opposed?

96
00:27:00,605 --> 00:27:01,666
[SPEAKER_25]: The motion passes.

97
00:27:01,686 --> 00:27:06,028
[SPEAKER_25]: 26039 offered by Councilor Tseng and Vice President Lazzaro.

98
00:27:06,629 --> 00:27:14,353
[SPEAKER_25]: Whereas Medford is home to a diverse and vibrant community representing many cultures, faith traditions, and heritages, and whereas residents across our city are celebrating Lunar New Year,

99
00:27:14,873 --> 00:27:20,418
[SPEAKER_25]: marking the beginning of a new year in many East and Southeast Asian cultures and honoring themes of renewal, family, and good fortune.

100
00:27:21,018 --> 00:27:26,262
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas Muslim residents of Medford are observing Ramadan, a sacred month of fasting, prayer, reflection, and charity.

101
00:27:26,963 --> 00:27:32,007
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas many Christian residents are observing Lent, a season of reflection, sacrifice, and spiritual renewal leading to Easter.

102
00:27:32,606 --> 00:27:43,515
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas these observances enrich our city through traditions of generosity, gathering, service, and hope, be it resolved that the Medford City Council extends its warm wishes to all residents celebrating Lunar New Year, observing Ramadan, and observing Lent.

103
00:27:43,995 --> 00:27:51,061
[SPEAKER_25]: And be it further resolved that the city of Medford reaffirms its commitment to being a welcoming and inclusive community where all cultures and faiths are respected and celebrated.

104
00:27:51,181 --> 00:27:51,882
[SPEAKER_25]: Councilor Tseng.

105
00:27:53,223 --> 00:27:54,263
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you, President Bears.

106
00:27:55,905 --> 00:28:00,368
[SPEAKER_23]: We're so lucky to have three majorly important

107
00:28:01,749 --> 00:28:06,052
[SPEAKER_23]: Cultural and faith, you know, events happening at the same time.

108
00:28:06,533 --> 00:28:12,538
[SPEAKER_23]: Three observances that reflect the rich cultural and faith traditions represented here in Medford.

109
00:28:13,318 --> 00:28:19,363
[SPEAKER_23]: One of the great strengths of our city is that so many different cultures, heritages, and faith traditions call Medford home.

110
00:28:19,944 --> 00:28:25,148
[SPEAKER_23]: And in this season especially, that diversity is visible in beautiful and meaningful ways.

111
00:28:26,235 --> 00:28:28,877
[SPEAKER_23]: Many of our neighbors are celebrating Lunar New Year.

112
00:28:29,097 --> 00:28:43,368
[SPEAKER_23]: I know I am, my family is, marking the beginning of a new year in East and Southeastern Asian cultures, a time that is centered on renewal, on family, gratitude, and hope for good fortune in the year ahead.

113
00:28:43,949 --> 00:28:50,714
[SPEAKER_23]: Certainly not limited to us, I wish that upon everyone else too, on behalf of the Asian community in Medford County.

114
00:28:51,952 --> 00:28:57,633
[SPEAKER_23]: Many of our Muslim neighbors are observing Ramadan, a sacred month of fasting, prayer, reflection, and charity.

115
00:28:58,353 --> 00:29:02,374
[SPEAKER_23]: It's a time that emphasizes discipline, generosity, and care for those in need.

116
00:29:03,294 --> 00:29:11,136
[SPEAKER_23]: And many of our Christian neighbors are observing Lent, a season of reflection, sacrifice, and spiritual renewal leading to Easter.

117
00:29:12,076 --> 00:29:15,957
[SPEAKER_23]: While these traditions are distinct, they share common values.

118
00:29:17,355 --> 00:29:23,141
[SPEAKER_23]: Like I said, reflection, renewal, generosity, family, community, and hope.

119
00:29:23,761 --> 00:29:34,772
[SPEAKER_23]: They remind us that even in a busy and sometimes divided world, we're connected by shared aspirations to care for one another, to strengthen our families, and to build a better future.

120
00:29:35,913 --> 00:29:38,795
[SPEAKER_23]: At Medford, that diversity is not something that separates us.

121
00:29:39,196 --> 00:29:40,317
[SPEAKER_23]: It's something that enriches us.

122
00:29:41,257 --> 00:29:44,057
[SPEAKER_23]: It means our children grow up learning about one another's traditions.

123
00:29:44,418 --> 00:29:52,339
[SPEAKER_23]: It means our neighborhoods are filled with different foods, languages, celebrations, houses of worship, different conversations about faith, values.

124
00:29:52,839 --> 00:29:58,640
[SPEAKER_23]: It means that we have the opportunity every single day in this community to practice respect and understanding.

125
00:29:59,720 --> 00:30:10,842
[SPEAKER_23]: This resolution simply extends our warm wishes to all residents observing these important seasons, and it reaffirms our commitment to being a welcoming and inclusive community, just like the previous resolution.

126
00:30:11,550 --> 00:30:15,434
[SPEAKER_23]: A community where every culture and every faith is respected and celebrated.

127
00:30:16,214 --> 00:30:22,260
[SPEAKER_23]: At a time when it can feel so easy to focus on what divides us, moments like this remind us of something deeper.

128
00:30:22,821 --> 00:30:30,268
[SPEAKER_23]: That we are one community, stronger because of our differences, and united in our shared commitment to making our city a better place.

129
00:30:32,750 --> 00:30:33,791
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, Councilor Tseng.

130
00:30:33,851 --> 00:30:34,772
[SPEAKER_25]: Vice President Lazzaro.

131
00:30:35,474 --> 00:30:35,894
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

132
00:30:36,975 --> 00:30:38,176
[SPEAKER_18]: Councilor Tseng put it really well.

133
00:30:38,797 --> 00:30:43,680
[SPEAKER_18]: This resolution is about celebrating the diversity of Medford.

134
00:30:43,740 --> 00:30:58,932
[SPEAKER_18]: We have many different faith traditions here and it's not common that Ramadan and Lent fall at the same time but I thought it was very interesting when I was explaining to my kids on Ash Wednesday because we are not, I was raised Catholic but I'm no longer a practicing Catholic.

135
00:30:58,972 --> 00:31:02,735
[SPEAKER_18]: I bring my kids to Unitarian Universalist Church in Medford and

136
00:31:03,636 --> 00:31:10,129
[SPEAKER_18]: They were asking me why people had ash crosses on their foreheads, and I used to do that as a kid.

137
00:31:11,772 --> 00:31:12,953
[SPEAKER_18]: all the way through college, actually.

138
00:31:13,674 --> 00:31:25,786
[SPEAKER_18]: And they, I was explaining to them, oh, it's the beginning of Lent when you give up something that you, that is a sacrifice for you because it brings you closer to God.

139
00:31:25,946 --> 00:31:29,509
[SPEAKER_18]: And then as I was explaining it, I was like, oh, you know what, it's actually a lot like Ramadan.

140
00:31:29,549 --> 00:31:31,651
[SPEAKER_18]: And actually, Ramadan is happening at the same time.

141
00:31:31,691 --> 00:31:33,834
[SPEAKER_18]: That's so interesting because I remember their,

142
00:31:34,434 --> 00:31:44,021
[SPEAKER_18]: have been times when Muslim friends of mine have been practicing Ramadan or observing Ramadan in the summer, and gosh, that's way harder because the days are so long.

143
00:31:44,082 --> 00:31:46,343
[SPEAKER_18]: But right now, the days are shorter, and that's convenient.

144
00:31:47,404 --> 00:31:58,152
[SPEAKER_18]: But it is a very similar practice where you sacrifice something for yourself, and that sacrifice and the struggle brings you some awareness of

145
00:32:03,055 --> 00:32:06,357
[SPEAKER_18]: a sense of meaning and it brings you closer to God.

146
00:32:06,437 --> 00:32:26,567
[SPEAKER_18]: So I thought that was a very interesting thing and when Councilor Tseng and I were talking about this resolution, that was something that I wanted to mention that there are often ways that these faith traditions and a lot of things about our human connectedness that bring us closer together rather than divide us.

147
00:32:26,748 --> 00:32:29,389
[SPEAKER_18]: So I think that's something that really

148
00:32:29,769 --> 00:32:38,212
[SPEAKER_18]: can come up a lot in Medford, that there are a lot of different practices that we do that are really more similar than they are different.

149
00:32:39,413 --> 00:32:44,495
[SPEAKER_18]: In addition, the year of the firehorse has just begun, which is an incredibly exciting thing.

150
00:32:45,495 --> 00:32:59,100
[SPEAKER_18]: It's characterized by power and drive and motivation to move forward and make progress, and I think that's a wonderful thing to celebrate and a great way to start the year and hopefully

151
00:33:00,148 --> 00:33:05,892
[SPEAKER_18]: We can use that drive and power to do more than just shoveling snow off our sidewalks in the coming months.

152
00:33:06,852 --> 00:33:16,438
[SPEAKER_18]: So I'm very excited about this resolution and wish the best of well wishes to everybody who's celebrating or observing these holidays.

153
00:33:16,838 --> 00:33:17,138
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

154
00:33:18,239 --> 00:33:18,719
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

155
00:33:18,879 --> 00:33:22,281
[SPEAKER_25]: On the motion of Councilor Tseng, seconded by Vice President Lazzaro to approve.

156
00:33:22,542 --> 00:33:23,082
[SPEAKER_25]: All those in favor?

157
00:33:24,068 --> 00:33:27,450
[SPEAKER_25]: Opposed, the motion passes.

158
00:33:27,470 --> 00:33:30,852
[SPEAKER_25]: 26040, resolution to celebrate National Therapy Animal Day by Vice President Lazzaro.

159
00:33:31,292 --> 00:33:38,656
[SPEAKER_25]: Whereas scientific research shows that interacting with therapy animals can reduce stress, relieve depression, slow heart rate, lower blood pressure, and strengthen the immune system.

160
00:33:39,457 --> 00:33:45,480
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas therapy animal teams in the city of Medford play an essential role in improving human health and well-being through the human-animal bond.

161
00:33:46,087 --> 00:34:04,940
[SPEAKER_25]: and whereas therapy animal teams interact with a variety of people in our community, including veterans, seniors, patients, students, and those approaching the end of life, and whereas those exceptional therapy animals who partner with their human companions bring comfort and healing to those in need, and whereas we encourage more pet owners to consider becoming pet partners and volunteers to help our community by creating greater access to meaningful therapy animal visits.

162
00:34:05,020 --> 00:34:10,464
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford City Council celebrate National Therapy Animal Day on April 30th.

163
00:34:10,504 --> 00:34:11,245
[SPEAKER_25]: Vice President Lazzaro.

164
00:34:12,223 --> 00:34:14,145
[SPEAKER_18]: I have so many nice resolutions today, guys.

165
00:34:15,746 --> 00:34:31,201
