1626
02:46:15,260 --> 02:46:17,301
[SPEAKER_25]: 26-046 offered by Councilor Callahan and President Paris.

1627
02:46:17,341 --> 02:46:20,082
[SPEAKER_25]: Resolution to support home sharing and request implementation plan.

1628
02:46:21,032 --> 02:46:31,022
[SPEAKER_25]: Whereas the City of Medford and in our entire region are in a housing affordability crisis and whereas over 65% of residents are singles or couples but less than 20% of our homes are studios or one bedrooms.

1629
02:46:31,543 --> 02:46:41,133
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas the City of Medford has a larger proportion of senior citizens than at any other time in recent memory, many seniors would like to age in place but have concerns about continuing to upkeep their houses or performing other basic tasks.

1630
02:46:41,713 --> 02:47:01,471
[SPEAKER_25]: and whereas building new housing takes time and may require zoning changes, and whereas home sharing has been shown in other communities to provide hundreds of units of affordable housing, keep seniors in their home and aging in place longer, reduce loneliness for senior citizens and increase a sense of community, all without infrastructure changes, and whereas the City of Medford on average added only 75 new units of housing per year from 2020 to 2024,

1631
02:47:03,473 --> 02:47:12,764
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas an advisor from the National Shared Housing Resource Center estimated that a city like Medford could expect to place 100 successful home shares in the first year and 500 each year after that.

1632
02:47:13,285 --> 02:47:17,350
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas home sharing program might require at least some funding and staff to run successfully.

1633
02:47:17,791 --> 02:47:22,877
[SPEAKER_25]: And whereas nearby towns might also benefit from a home sharing program and may be willing to share the benefits and costs of such a program.

1634
02:47:23,397 --> 02:47:34,028
[SPEAKER_25]: Therefore, be it resolved that the City Council recognizes home sharing as an important cost effective tool to increasing housing availability and affordability, supporting aging in place and reducing loneliness and expresses its intent

1635
02:47:34,466 --> 02:47:46,815
[SPEAKER_25]: to consider funding such a program as part of the FY27 operating budget and be it further resolved that the City Council hereby request that the Mayor, through the appropriate departments, provide the Council with a written response no later than March 31st that does one of the following.

1636
02:47:47,336 --> 02:47:58,584
[SPEAKER_25]: One provides an implementation plan for home sharing which could include a proposed program model and administrative home, estimated staffing and operational requirements, estimate of funding, a proposed timeline for launch,

1637
02:47:59,693 --> 02:48:04,778
[SPEAKER_25]: and identification of any opportunities for grants, partnerships, or cost sharing when they bring municipalities.

1638
02:48:05,319 --> 02:48:14,588
[SPEAKER_25]: Or two, states of the administration does not intend to prioritize implementation of home sharing in fiscal 27 with a brief explanation sufficient to inform the city council's budget deliberations.

1639
02:48:15,729 --> 02:48:16,670
[SPEAKER_25]: Councilor Callahan.

1640
02:48:17,629 --> 02:48:17,929
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

1641
02:48:18,149 --> 02:48:20,090
[SPEAKER_12]: I just want to give a little bit of background.

1642
02:48:20,851 --> 02:48:27,554
[SPEAKER_12]: So I'm sure everyone knows that housing and the cost of housing especially is really at a critical point.

1643
02:48:28,095 --> 02:48:33,418
[SPEAKER_12]: So many residents that I have talked to are increasingly concerned about it whether they are homeowners or renters.

1644
02:48:34,839 --> 02:48:59,780
[SPEAKER_12]: And, you know, I really heard, especially when I knocked on thousands of doors my first election cycle, so many seniors that I talked to really talked about their concerns about being able to stay in their homes, you know, not knowing how long they would be able to age in place, also not knowing where, even if they could move, which they didn't want to,

1645
02:49:00,740 --> 02:49:07,765
[SPEAKER_12]: where they would move in Medford, that they wanted to live near their neighbors, and they lived there for 20 years, 50 years, their entire lives.

1646
02:49:08,945 --> 02:49:18,311
[SPEAKER_12]: I just heard this over and over, and I am always looking for creative solutions to our problems that have worked in other cities.

1647
02:49:21,328 --> 02:49:32,715
[SPEAKER_12]: I also have one of the things that I noticed early on as I was looking at housing is that 50 years ago Medford had maybe 8 or 9,000 more people living here with less housing.

1648
02:49:36,877 --> 02:49:54,106
[SPEAKER_12]: putting all these things together and then looking at other cities to find out what other cities have done to sort of solve this problem that we have, a lot of which is, you know, older senior residents who have a home that has maybe four or five bedrooms.

1649
02:49:54,126 --> 02:49:55,647
[SPEAKER_12]: There's only one or two people living there.

1650
02:49:56,347 --> 02:50:01,570
[SPEAKER_12]: That causes, you know, a little bit of a crunch for us in terms of housing.

1651
02:50:03,031 --> 02:50:10,879
[SPEAKER_12]: But I know from my mom, you know, she moved to the area to be closer to me and my sister the two years before she died.

1652
02:50:10,899 --> 02:50:11,840
[SPEAKER_12]: She died a year and a half ago.

1653
02:50:13,101 --> 02:50:15,263
[SPEAKER_12]: She was in her she was 85 when she moved here.

1654
02:50:15,843 --> 02:50:17,965
[SPEAKER_12]: And even just her moving

1655
02:50:19,446 --> 02:50:23,467
[SPEAKER_12]: into an apartment here with us living very, very close.

1656
02:50:23,807 --> 02:50:28,228
[SPEAKER_12]: It was incredibly stressful in ways we never anticipated.

1657
02:50:28,248 --> 02:50:38,771
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, she seemed to be sharp as a tack and, you know, she certainly appeared to be cognitively all there, but we realized after she moved that,

1658
02:50:39,671 --> 02:50:44,355
[SPEAKER_12]: she was running a lot of her life on kinesthetic memory of how her apartment functioned.

1659
02:50:44,895 --> 02:50:49,339
[SPEAKER_12]: And she had trouble turning on her dishwasher, which had a button that said start.

1660
02:50:49,780 --> 02:50:59,808
[SPEAKER_12]: Like, you know, the things that she was unable to do and that gave her so much anxiety were unpredictable for us and really difficult.

1661
02:50:59,868 --> 02:51:05,533
[SPEAKER_12]: And so I really have compassion for people who do not want to move when they are older.

1662
02:51:07,895 --> 02:51:11,699
[SPEAKER_12]: But also keeping up your home can become quite difficult.

1663
02:51:11,719 --> 02:51:15,983
[SPEAKER_12]: A lot of the seniors are lower income than the people who have moved in since then.

1664
02:51:18,365 --> 02:51:23,390
[SPEAKER_12]: Medford was that place where you could afford to buy when you were working class person 50 years ago, 30 years ago.

1665
02:51:25,832 --> 02:51:36,188
[SPEAKER_12]: So, as I looked at other communities, it became clear that many other cities across the country are having similar problems that we are having.

1666
02:51:36,248 --> 02:51:38,211
[SPEAKER_12]: Just it's the baby boomer generation.

1667
02:51:40,854 --> 02:51:53,883
[SPEAKER_12]: there was this solution that really appealed to me that has worked in some cities for five years, in some cities for 25 years, and it's called home sharing.

1668
02:51:53,963 --> 02:52:06,912
[SPEAKER_12]: Home sharing is basically a matchmaking service that helps older senior residents or senior residents who have extra rooms in their home to find one person

1669
02:52:08,093 --> 02:52:23,198
[SPEAKER_12]: who is a little younger than they are and who can help them to stay in their homes longer and they usually pay some portion of monthly payment and they also often have an agreement to help around the house.

1670
02:52:23,858 --> 02:52:27,819
[SPEAKER_12]: So it's usually really beneficial for both parties.

1671
02:52:28,759 --> 02:52:34,161
[SPEAKER_12]: It has proven to be incredibly successful in other communities that have similar demographics to ours.

1672
02:52:35,181 --> 02:52:46,067
[SPEAKER_12]: And, you know, we've, there are a number of other volunteers who work with me and have been working with me on this project for probably about a year and a half.

1673
02:52:46,767 --> 02:52:56,232
[SPEAKER_12]: And what we, we've done a lot of legwork and some of that legwork has included the housing staff person here in Medford.

1674
02:52:56,732 --> 02:53:04,356
[SPEAKER_12]: So, that staff person is kind of up to date on the things that we've talked about and the discoveries that we've made.

1675
02:53:05,676 --> 02:53:15,258
[SPEAKER_12]: There are private organizations, both nonprofits as well as for-profits, that could come in to our community and offer these kinds of services.

1676
02:53:16,558 --> 02:53:21,719
[SPEAKER_12]: Sometimes they require an agreement with the city, sometimes require some form of payment from the city.

1677
02:53:22,939 --> 02:53:31,361
[SPEAKER_12]: Also, we really think that this could be attractive to other communities, Somerville, Malden, Arlington, who knows, and that

1678
02:53:32,221 --> 02:53:44,247
[SPEAKER_12]: having the city of Medford reach out to other communities to ask whether they would be interested in sort of having a joint, you know, two city, three city approach where the cost would be much less.

1679
02:53:44,928 --> 02:53:47,589
[SPEAKER_12]: It often does not take a lot of people.

1680
02:53:47,629 --> 02:53:49,110
[SPEAKER_12]: It could be one staff person.

1681
02:53:49,130 --> 02:53:52,532
[SPEAKER_12]: It could start off with a half a staff person divided between cities.

1682
02:53:52,992 --> 02:54:00,176
[SPEAKER_12]: But essentially what we came to was an understanding that we had done enough research

1683
02:54:00,936 --> 02:54:13,724
[SPEAKER_12]: to come to the point where without the city of Medford being able to make some calls and to commit in some way that we cannot move forward any further as a volunteer organization.

1684
02:54:14,024 --> 02:54:29,653
[SPEAKER_12]: So, it is going to require the city of Medford to just state that it is interested in this and to put even a tiny amount of resources into it, which could be the housing planner spending a few hours,

1685
02:54:30,514 --> 02:54:37,580
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, making some phone calls and then some decisions being made within the planning department about, you know, how this is moving forward.

1686
02:54:37,600 --> 02:54:43,686
[SPEAKER_12]: And really the request from the administration is not a large one.

1687
02:54:43,706 --> 02:54:45,748
[SPEAKER_12]: It is simply to understand.

1688
02:54:46,268 --> 02:55:01,348
[SPEAKER_12]: whether they will devote some resources, and again, some resources could be a very small amount of resources, to further investigate and to get enough knowledge to understand whether this kind of program would be able to move forward.

1689
02:55:03,811 --> 02:55:17,085
[SPEAKER_12]: If we even had an agreement from the mayor that we would have one staff person who would spend a few hours reaching out and doing some research to come up with some sort of a conclusion, that could be sufficient as well, but that is resources.

1690
02:55:19,988 --> 02:55:40,478
[SPEAKER_12]: What we're looking for here is we think that we have found a really excellent solution that could provide Medford with something that we need, which is a lot of affordable housing very easily with no zoning changes, with no new development, with no change to the infrastructure.

1691
02:55:42,019 --> 02:55:44,019
[SPEAKER_12]: I certainly believe in all the tools,

1692
02:55:45,240 --> 02:55:50,505
[SPEAKER_12]: in the tool belt that we can have to tackle our affordable housing crisis here.

1693
02:55:50,845 --> 02:55:52,226
[SPEAKER_12]: This is simply one tool.

1694
02:55:52,286 --> 02:55:53,367
[SPEAKER_12]: It's not a panacea.

1695
02:55:53,627 --> 02:55:54,788
[SPEAKER_12]: It's not going to resolve everything.

1696
02:55:55,088 --> 02:56:02,214
[SPEAKER_12]: But it would be a great tool to have in our tool belt given how much it sort of matches what we need.

1697
02:56:02,314 --> 02:56:03,495
[SPEAKER_12]: It's very inexpensive.

1698
02:56:03,816 --> 02:56:05,257
[SPEAKER_12]: We could collaborate with other cities.

1699
02:56:05,917 --> 02:56:08,820
[SPEAKER_12]: I just would love to sort of, you know,

1700
02:56:10,120 --> 02:56:19,030
[SPEAKER_12]: ask the administration for a yes or no answer, and with a little bit of detail as to whether or not they will be able to move forward with something like this.

1701
02:56:19,330 --> 02:56:19,831
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you so much.

1702
02:56:19,851 --> 02:56:24,375
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, Councilor Callahan, and thank you for letting me co-sponsor this with you.

1703
02:56:24,415 --> 02:56:29,421
[SPEAKER_25]: I think this is one of the many tools that we could use to try to match folks.

1704
02:56:31,034 --> 02:56:45,717
[SPEAKER_25]: who may want support in their home, whether that's support around the house or financial support or moral support, emotional support, with folks who are trying to be good neighbors, maybe younger folks who are trying to stay in the community.

1705
02:56:46,858 --> 02:56:57,400
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it's just a great way to try to link people, because I think one of the biggest gaps that we find in this day and age is that it's harder than ever to make connections and build community.

1706
02:56:57,500 --> 02:56:59,761
[SPEAKER_25]: So if we could build a program that people trusted,

1707
02:57:01,223 --> 02:57:01,588
[SPEAKER_25]: And that...

1708
02:57:02,144 --> 02:57:15,368
[SPEAKER_25]: you know, had all of the procedures in place and the security, the verification, you know, everything that we need to make sure that, you know, if the city is going to get involved, that folks are getting matched up, you know, as best as we can.

1709
02:57:15,388 --> 02:57:28,591
[SPEAKER_25]: Never going to be perfect, but folks who are struggling to stay in the city, whether they're young or old, putting them together so that both folks can stay, I think is a really noble cause and something we should work on.

1710
02:57:29,071 --> 02:57:29,712
[SPEAKER_25]: So, thank you.

1711
02:57:30,492 --> 02:57:30,992
[SPEAKER_25]: Councilor Tseng.

1712
02:57:33,331 --> 02:57:39,776
[SPEAKER_23]: I just wanted to thank Councilor Callaghan for putting forward such an innovative idea to tackle the housing crisis here in Medford.

1713
02:57:40,756 --> 02:57:45,780
[SPEAKER_23]: I think I've always said that we need as many tools in the toolbox as possible to tackle the challenge.

